 This problem is about strings on alphabet {A,B,C} with certain restriction, we'll call this Set P. We assign 0,1 and 2 (\textit{mod} 3) to sets A, B and C, then we'll analyze the composition by these assignments.</think> <answer> Let $f(n)$ be the total number of the seven-letter strings in $\textnormal{P}$ and $f_k(n)$ be the total number of the seven-letter strings in $\textnormal{P}$ ending at the integer $n$. Then we investagate $f_k(n)$ with recurrence relation as follows:
\begin{align*}
    f_0(n) &= f_0(n-1)+f_2(n-1) \\ 
    f_1(n) &= f_0(n-1)+f_1(n-1) \\ 
    f_2(n) &= f_1(n-1)+f_2(n-1);\, \quad k\, (\text{even}) \\ 
    f_0(n) &= f_1(n-1)+f_2(n-1) \\ 
    f_1(n) &= f_0(n-1)+f_1(n-1) \\ 
    f_2(n) &= f_1(n-1)+f_2(n-1);\, \quad k\, (\text{odd}) \\ 
    f(7) &=  \sum_{k=0}^2 \sum_{n=0}^{2}f_k(n).
\end{align*}
    \end{align*}
Now let us find $f_k(n)$:
\begin{align*}
    f_0(n)&=f_2(n-1)+f_2(n-1)=2f_2(n-1) \\ 
    f_1(n)&=f_0(n-1)+f_1(n-1)=f_0(n-2)+2f_1(n-1)-f_1(n-1)=f_0(n-2)+f_1(n-1) \\ 
    f_2(n)&=f_0(n-1)+f_2(n-2)=f_0(n-2)+2f_2(n-2).
\end{align*}
Thereafter we obtain
\begin{align*} 
    f_0(n) &=2f_2(n-1) \\ 
        &=2(f_0(n-2)+2f_2(n-3))=\ldots=2^{n-3}f_0(n-(n-3))=2^{n-3}f_0(3)=(2^2+2^1+2^0)2^{4-n} \\ 
    f_1(n)&=(2^2+2^1+2^0)2^{3-n} \\ 
    f_2(n)&=(2^2+2^1+2^0)2^{3-n}.
\end{align*}
Hence,\begin{align*} 
    f(7)&=3(2^2+2^1+2^0)2^{-3}=3*3/4=9/4
\end{align*}
This is the imaginary answer, but I was confused about the interpretations of $k$ in the process. Therfore, below conclusion is made. $\#
f_0(7)=\sum_{k=0}^2 f_k(7)=9 (mod 4), f_1(7)= f_2(7)=6 (mod 4)$</answer>

problem:
Two points are drawn on each side of a square with an area of 81 square units, dividing the side into 3 congruent parts.  Quarter-circle arcs connect the points on adjacent sides to create the figure shown.  What is the length of the boundary of the bolded figure?  Express your answer as a decimal to the nearest tenth. [asy]
size(80);
import graph;
draw((0,0)--(3,0)--(3,3)--(0,3)--cycle, linetype("2 4"));
draw(Arc((0,0),1,0,90),linewidth(.8));
draw(Arc((0,3),1,0,-90),linewidth(.8));
draw(Arc((3,0),1,90,180),linewidth(.8));
draw(Arc((3,3),1,180,270),linewidth(.8));
draw((1,0)--(2,0),linewidth(.8));draw((3,1)--(3,2),linewidth(.8));
draw((1,3)--(2,3),linewidth(.8));draw((0,1)--(0,2),linewidth(.8));
[/asy]

